WEBVTT

03:19.349 --> 03:20.599
Hello.

03:21.559 --> 03:24.228
My name's Forrest. Forrest Gump.

03:29.776 --> 03:31.819
Do you want a chocolate?

03:34.405 --> 03:37.825
I could eat about
a million and a half of these.

03:38.993 --> 03:44.206
My mama always said
life was like a box of chocolates.

03:46.209 --> 03:49.086
You never know what you're gonna get.

03:56.302 --> 03:58.846
Those must be comfortable shoes.

04:00.223 --> 04:04.893
I'll bet you could walk all day
in shoes like that and not feel a thing.

04:07.105 --> 04:09.565
I wish I had shoes like that.

04:10.232 --> 04:11.774
My feet hurt.

04:12.985 --> 04:14.652
Mama always said there's an awful lot

04:14.736 --> 04:17.947
you could tell about a person
by their shoes:

04:19.074 --> 04:22.034
Where they're going,
where they've been.

04:29.293 --> 04:31.335
I've worn lots of shoes.

04:34.464 --> 04:39.260
I bet if I think about it real hard,
I could remember my first pair of shoes.

04:42.181 --> 04:44.807
Mama said they'd take me anywhere.

04:45.601 --> 04:48.227
She said they was my magic shoes.

04:48.312 --> 04:51.480
All right, Forrest,
you can open your eyes now.

04:58.780 --> 05:01.240
Let's take a little walk around.

05:08.040 --> 05:09.832
How do those feel?

05:12.794 --> 05:14.962
His legs are strong, Mrs. Gump,

05:15.047 --> 05:17.548
as strong as I've ever seen,

05:17.633 --> 05:21.010
but his back is as crooked
as a politician.

05:22.304 --> 05:25.389
But we're gonna straighten him right up,
now, aren't we, Forrest?

05:25.474 --> 05:26.599
Forrest!

05:28.101 --> 05:29.310
Now, when I was a baby,

05:29.394 --> 05:32.230
Mama named me after
the great Civil War hero,

05:32.314 --> 05:34.732
General Nathan Bedford Forrest.

05:34.816 --> 05:37.026
She said we was related to him
in some way.

05:37.110 --> 05:38.486
And what he did was,

05:38.570 --> 05:42.823
he started up this club called
the Ku Klux Klan.

05:42.908 --> 05:46.244
They'd all dress up in their robes
and their bed sheets

05:46.328 --> 05:50.665
and act like a bunch of ghosts
or spooks or something.

05:50.749 --> 05:54.627
They'd even put bed sheets
on their horses and ride around.

05:54.711 --> 05:57.755
And anyway, that's how I got my name,

05:57.839 --> 05:59.257
Forrest Gump.

05:59.341 --> 06:01.092
Mama said that the "Forrest" part

06:01.176 --> 06:04.720
was to remind me that sometimes
we all do things that,

06:04.805 --> 06:07.598
well, just don't make no sense.

06:13.272 --> 06:16.774
Okay... Get it, get it...

06:16.858 --> 06:19.819
Wait, is it this way? Hold on.

06:20.737 --> 06:22.238
All right...

06:22.823 --> 06:24.490
What are you all staring at?

06:24.574 --> 06:29.036
Haven't you ever seen a little boy
with braces on his legs before?

06:30.580 --> 06:34.292
Don't ever let anybody tell you
they're better than you, Forrest.

06:34.376 --> 06:36.961
If God intended
everybody to be the same,

06:37.045 --> 06:39.170
he'd have given us all braces
on our legs.

06:39.255 --> 06:40.964
Mama always had a way of
explaining things

06:41.048 --> 06:43.049
so I could understand them.

06:44.510 --> 06:48.013
We lived about a quarter mile
off Route 17,

06:48.097 --> 06:51.141
about a half mile from
the town of Greenbow, Alabama.

06:51.225 --> 06:53.977
That's in the county of Greenbow.

06:54.061 --> 06:58.481
Our house had been in Mama's family
since her grandpa's grandpa's grandpa

06:58.566 --> 07:00.483
had come across the ocean
about 1,000 years ago,

07:00.568 --> 07:02.485
something like that.

07:02.570 --> 07:05.280
Since it was just me and Mama
and we had all these empty rooms,

07:05.364 --> 07:08.116
Mama decided to let those rooms out,

07:08.200 --> 07:10.160
mostly to people passing through,

07:10.244 --> 07:14.205
like from, oh, Mobile,
Montgomery, places like that.

07:14.290 --> 07:17.000
That's how me and Mama got money.

07:17.084 --> 07:19.836
Mama was a real smart lady.

07:19.920 --> 07:24.924
Remember what I told you, Forrest.
You're no different than anybody else is.

07:27.428 --> 07:29.804
Did you hear what I said, Forrest?

07:29.889 --> 07:34.059
You're the same as everybody else.
You are no different.

07:34.560 --> 07:39.022
Your boy's different, Mrs. Gump.

07:39.106 --> 07:41.316
Now, his IQ is 75.

07:42.109 --> 07:45.236
Well, we're all different, Mr. Hancock.

07:48.824 --> 07:50.867
She wanted me to have
the finest education,

07:50.951 --> 07:54.871
so she took me to
the Greenbow County Central School.

07:54.955 --> 07:57.207
I met the principal and all.

07:57.708 --> 08:00.585
I want to show you something,
Mrs. Gump.

08:01.045 --> 08:03.922
Now, this is normal.

08:04.423 --> 08:07.717
Forrest is right here.

08:08.552 --> 08:14.099
The state requires a minimum IQ of
80 to attend public school, Mrs. Gump.

08:14.600 --> 08:17.477
He's gonna have to go
to a special school.

08:17.561 --> 08:19.687
Now, he'll be just fine.

08:20.481 --> 08:22.565
What does "normal" mean, anyway?

08:22.650 --> 08:26.027
He might be a bit on the slow side,

08:27.154 --> 08:28.905
but my boy Forrest is gonna get

08:28.989 --> 08:31.533
the same opportunities
as everyone else.

08:31.617 --> 08:35.412
He's not going to some special school
to learn how to re-tread tires.

08:35.496 --> 08:38.664
We're talking about
five little points here.

08:40.376 --> 08:43.001
There must be something can be done.

08:44.588 --> 08:47.048
We're a progressive school system.

08:47.883 --> 08:50.802
We don't want to see anybody
left behind.

08:51.679 --> 08:55.140
Is there a Mr. Gump, Mrs. Gump?

08:58.394 --> 09:00.270
He's on vacation.

09:17.745 --> 09:21.540
Well, your mama sure does care
about your schooling, son.

09:27.046 --> 09:29.506
You don't say much, do you?

09:41.019 --> 09:42.978
"Finally, he had to try.

09:43.062 --> 09:45.022
"It looked easy, but,

09:46.232 --> 09:48.567
"oh, what happened.

09:48.651 --> 09:51.653
- "First, there... "
- Mama, what's "vacation" mean?

09:52.197 --> 09:54.781
- Vacation?
- Where Daddy went.

09:57.410 --> 10:00.120
Vacation's when you go somewhere

10:02.499 --> 10:04.833
and you don't ever come back.

10:09.172 --> 10:12.966
Anyway, I guess you could
say me and Mama was on our own.

10:14.177 --> 10:17.804
But we didn't mind.
Our house was never empty.

10:17.889 --> 10:20.474
There was always folks
coming and going.

10:20.558 --> 10:21.642
Supper.

10:21.726 --> 10:25.145
- It's supper, everyone. Forrest...
- My, my. That sure looks special.

10:25.230 --> 10:27.773
Sometimes we had
so many people staying with us

10:27.857 --> 10:30.526
that every room
was filled with travelers.

10:30.610 --> 10:34.238
You know, folks living out
of their suitcases

10:34.322 --> 10:37.282
and hat cases and sample cases.

10:37.367 --> 10:40.786
Forrest Gump, it's supper time! Forrest...

10:40.870 --> 10:43.413
One time, a young man
was staying with us,

10:43.498 --> 10:47.125
and he had him a guitar case.

11:01.099 --> 11:05.102
Forrest! I told you not to bother
this nice young man.

11:05.186 --> 11:06.520
Oh, no, that's all right, ma'am.

11:06.604 --> 11:09.439
I was just showing him a thing or two
on the guitar here.

11:09.524 --> 11:12.484
All right, but your supper's ready
if y'all want to eat.

11:12.569 --> 11:15.529
Yeah, that sounds good.
Thank you, ma'am.

11:16.197 --> 11:19.783
Say, man, show me that crazy
little walk you just did there.

11:19.867 --> 11:21.743
Slow it down some.

11:23.871 --> 11:25.789
I liked that guitar.

11:26.457 --> 11:28.208
It sounded good.

11:30.003 --> 11:34.172
I started moving around to the music,

11:34.257 --> 11:36.090
swinging my hips.

11:38.677 --> 11:41.220
This one night,
me and Mama was out shopping,

11:41.305 --> 11:44.307
and we walked right by
Benson's furniture and appliance store,

11:44.391 --> 11:45.975
and guess what?

11:58.322 --> 12:01.157
This is not for children's eyes.

12:03.702 --> 12:05.494
Some years later,
that handsome young man

12:05.579 --> 12:08.122
who they called "The King,"

12:08.206 --> 12:10.541
well, he'd sung too many songs,

12:11.209 --> 12:13.753
had himself a heart attack,
or something.

12:14.838 --> 12:17.006
Must be hard being a king.

12:21.303 --> 12:24.138
You know, it's funny how you remember
some things, but some things you can't.

12:24.890 --> 12:28.768
- You do your very best now, Forrest.
- I sure will, Mama.

12:30.479 --> 12:35.066
I remember the bus ride
on the first day of school very well.

12:38.612 --> 12:40.321
Are you coming along?

12:40.405 --> 12:43.908
Mama said not to be taking
rides from strangers.

12:43.992 --> 12:46.160
This is the bus to school.

12:49.122 --> 12:51.374
I'm Forrest. Forrest Gump.

12:52.334 --> 12:56.337
- I'm Dorothy Harris.
- Well, now we ain't strangers anymore.

13:09.351 --> 13:11.143
This seat's taken.

13:13.605 --> 13:15.106
It's taken!

13:22.989 --> 13:24.865
You can't sit here.

13:27.035 --> 13:30.454
You know, it's funny what
a young man recollects,

13:30.539 --> 13:32.915
'cause I don't remember being born.

13:34.543 --> 13:36.711
I don't recall what I got
for my first Christmas,

13:36.795 --> 13:39.880
and I don't know when I went
on my first outdoor picnic.

13:39.965 --> 13:44.677
But I do remember the first time I heard

13:44.761 --> 13:47.596
the sweetest voice in the wide world.

13:48.098 --> 13:50.474
You can sit here if you want.

13:53.395 --> 13:57.273
I had never seen anything
so beautiful in my life.

13:57.983 --> 14:00.067
She was like an angel.

14:00.152 --> 14:03.069
Well, are you gonna sit down,
or aren't you?

14:08.033 --> 14:09.826
What's wrong with your legs?

14:09.910 --> 14:14.164
Nothing at all, thank you.
My legs are just fine and dandy.

14:15.082 --> 14:17.250
I just sat next to her on that bus

14:17.334 --> 14:19.419
and had a conversation
all the way to school.

14:19.503 --> 14:22.213
...my back's crooked like
a question mark.

14:22.298 --> 14:23.465
These are going to make me...

14:23.549 --> 14:28.303
And next to Mama, no one ever
talked to me or asked me questions.

14:28.846 --> 14:30.805
Are you stupid or something?

14:30.890 --> 14:33.892
Mama says, "Stupid is as stupid does. "

14:35.519 --> 14:39.189
- I'm Jenny.
- I'm Forrest. Forrest Gump.

14:39.857 --> 14:41.691
From that day on,
we was always together.

14:41.776 --> 14:44.611
Jenny and me was like
peas and carrots.

14:48.199 --> 14:49.824
She taught me how to climb.

14:49.909 --> 14:52.619
Come on, Forrest, you can do it.

14:52.703 --> 14:55.330
I showed her how to dangle.

14:55.414 --> 14:57.457
"... a good little monkey and... "

14:57.541 --> 15:02.462
She helped me learn how to read,
and I showed her how to swing.

15:04.799 --> 15:08.551
Sometimes we'd just sit out
and wait for the stars.

15:08.636 --> 15:13.556
- Mama's gonna worry about me.
- Just stay a little longer.

15:14.809 --> 15:18.561
For some reason,
Jenny didn't never want to go home.

15:18.646 --> 15:20.730
Okay, Jenny, I'll stay.

15:21.565 --> 15:24.317
She was my most special friend.

15:27.738 --> 15:29.405
My only friend.

15:33.202 --> 15:36.996
Now, my mama always told me that
miracles happen every day.

15:37.081 --> 15:39.457
Some people don't think so, but they do.

15:42.503 --> 15:44.087
Hey, dummy!

15:45.047 --> 15:47.131
Are you retarded, or just plain stupid?

15:47.216 --> 15:50.718
- "Look, I'm Forrest Gimp. "
Just run away, Forrest.

15:52.054 --> 15:55.139
Run, Forrest! Run away! Hurry!

15:55.224 --> 15:58.476
- Get the bikes!
Hurry up! Let's get him!

15:58.561 --> 16:01.104
- Come on!
- Look out, dummy, here we come!

16:01.188 --> 16:03.022
We're gonna get you!

16:03.983 --> 16:07.735
Run, Forrest, run! Run, Forrest!

16:09.446 --> 16:11.364
Come back here, you!

16:25.004 --> 16:27.463
Run, Forrest!

16:27.548 --> 16:28.965
Run!

17:00.163 --> 17:03.040
Now, you wouldn't believe it
if I told you,

17:04.166 --> 17:06.667
but I can run like the wind blows.

17:09.923 --> 17:13.008
From that day on,
if I was going somewhere,

17:13.843 --> 17:15.135
I was running!

17:15.219 --> 17:17.596
He's getting away! Stop him!

17:49.045 --> 17:52.047
That boy sure is a running fool.

17:56.260 --> 17:57.636
Now, remember how I told you that

17:57.720 --> 18:00.639
Jenny never seemed
to want to go home?

18:00.723 --> 18:03.809
Well, she lived in a house
that was as old as Alabama.

18:03.893 --> 18:06.061
Her mama had gone up to heaven
when she was five,

18:06.145 --> 18:09.481
and her daddy was
some kind of a farmer.

18:11.317 --> 18:12.359
Jenny?

18:12.443 --> 18:14.611
He was a very loving man.

18:15.071 --> 18:19.324
He was always kissing and touching
her and her sisters.

18:21.077 --> 18:25.497
And then this one time,
Jenny wasn't on the bus to go to school.

18:26.666 --> 18:28.625
Jenny, why didn't you come
to school today?

18:29.794 --> 18:31.670
Daddy's taking a nap.

18:31.754 --> 18:33.463
Jenny!
- Come on!

18:34.924 --> 18:37.467
Jenny, where'd you run to?

18:38.803 --> 18:41.471
You'd better get back here, girl!

18:42.932 --> 18:44.599
Where you at?

18:47.979 --> 18:51.273
Jenny! Jenny! Where you at?

18:54.277 --> 18:55.610
Jenny!

18:55.695 --> 18:58.655
Pray with me, Forrest. Pray with me.

18:58.781 --> 18:59.905
Jenny!

18:59.990 --> 19:03.200
Dear God, make me a bird
so I can fly far,

19:03.285 --> 19:05.036
far, far away from here.

19:05.120 --> 19:08.789
Dear God, make me a bird
so I can fly far,

19:08.874 --> 19:09.999
far, far away from here.

19:10.125 --> 19:13.169
Mama always said
that God is mysterious.

19:13.295 --> 19:14.420
Jenny!

19:14.504 --> 19:16.839
He didn't turn Jenny into a bird that day.

19:16.965 --> 19:18.049
You'd better get back here!

19:18.133 --> 19:19.633
Instead,

19:20.302 --> 19:24.847
he had the police say Jenny didn't
have to stay in that house no more.

19:25.307 --> 19:29.018
She went to live with her grandma
just over on Creekmore Avenue,

19:29.144 --> 19:32.313
which made me happy,
'cause she was so close.

19:34.900 --> 19:39.945
Some nights, Jenny would sneak out
and come on over to my house,

19:40.030 --> 19:43.157
just 'cause she said she was scared.

19:43.241 --> 19:45.701
Scared of what, I don't know,

19:45.827 --> 19:49.038
but I think it was her grandma's dog.

19:49.164 --> 19:50.915
He was a mean dog.

19:51.666 --> 19:54.376
Anyway, Jenny and me was best friends

19:54.461 --> 19:55.753
all the way up through high school.

19:57.714 --> 19:59.757
- Hey, stupid!
- Quit it!

20:00.884 --> 20:03.177
- Run, Forrest, run!
- Hey,

20:03.887 --> 20:05.346
did you hear me, stupid?

20:05.430 --> 20:06.639
- Run, Forrest!
- Come on, get in the truck!

20:06.723 --> 20:08.849
Get in the truck! Let's move it!

20:08.934 --> 20:11.685
Come on, he's getting away! Move it!

20:11.770 --> 20:13.938
Run, Forrest! Run!

20:14.022 --> 20:17.566
You better be running, stupid!
Come on, dummy!

20:19.528 --> 20:23.030
- Haul ass, dummy!
- Yeah, you better get running!

20:26.034 --> 20:27.701
Jack rabbit!

20:36.128 --> 20:37.378
Yeah!

20:38.213 --> 20:40.381
Go! Go! Go!

20:42.092 --> 20:43.717
Run, Forrest!

20:46.721 --> 20:50.307
Now, it used to be,
I ran to get where I was going,

20:51.893 --> 20:54.395
I never thought it would
take me anywhere.

21:23.425 --> 21:27.595
- Who in the hell is that?
- That there is Forrest Gump, Coach.

21:28.596 --> 21:30.430
Just a local idiot.

21:31.098 --> 21:34.601
And can you believe it?
I got to go to college, too.

21:41.192 --> 21:43.818
Forrest! Forrest! Run!

21:43.944 --> 21:45.528
- Okay!
- Run!

21:45.613 --> 21:49.157
Run, you stupid son of a bitch! Run!

22:00.628 --> 22:04.172
You son of a bitch! Run! Go! Run!

22:06.550 --> 22:09.302
No! Turn! Go!

22:20.522 --> 22:24.150
He must be the stupidest
son of a bitch alive,

22:24.235 --> 22:26.110
but he sure is fast!

22:29.156 --> 22:34.160
Now, maybe it's just me,
but college was very confusing times.

22:35.496 --> 22:37.413
Federal troops enforcing a court order

22:37.498 --> 22:40.500
integrated the University
of Alabama today.

22:40.584 --> 22:41.793
Two negroes were admitted,

22:41.877 --> 22:45.171
but only after Governor George Wallace
had carried out his symbolic threat

22:45.256 --> 22:46.798
to stand in the school house door.

22:46.882 --> 22:51.552
Governor Wallace,
I take it from that statement, that...

22:51.679 --> 22:53.680
Earl, what's going on?

22:53.764 --> 22:57.100
- Coons are trying to get into school.
- Coons?

22:57.184 --> 22:58.851
When raccoons try to get
on our back porch,

22:58.936 --> 23:00.728
Mama just chase them off with a broom.

23:00.854 --> 23:05.358
Not raccoons, you idiot, niggers,
and they want to go to school with us.

23:05.859 --> 23:07.902
With us? They do?

23:08.862 --> 23:11.364
Shortly after Governor
Wallace had carried out his promise

23:11.448 --> 23:12.657
to block the doorway,

23:12.741 --> 23:14.701
President Kennedy
ordered the Secretary of Defense

23:14.785 --> 23:16.786
then to use military force.

23:16.870 --> 23:19.580
Here, by videotape,
is the encounter by General Graham,

23:19.707 --> 23:22.959
commander of the National Guard,
and Governor Wallace.

23:23.043 --> 23:26.754
...because these National Guardsmen
are here today

23:26.839 --> 23:29.382
as federal soldiers for Alabamans.

23:29.466 --> 23:33.386
They live within our borders,
they are all our brothers.

23:33.470 --> 23:35.888
We are winning in this fight,

23:35.973 --> 23:38.975
because we are awakening
the American people

23:39.059 --> 23:42.395
to the dangers that we have spoken
about so many times,

23:42.479 --> 23:48.776
just so evident today, the trend towards
military dictatorship in this country.

23:52.239 --> 23:54.699
And so, at day's end,
the University of Alabama

23:54.783 --> 23:57.075
in Tuscaloosa had been desegregated

23:57.160 --> 24:00.162
and students Jimmy Hood
and Vivian Malone

24:00.246 --> 24:03.332
had been signed up
for summer classes.

24:05.918 --> 24:08.754
Ma'am, you dropped your book.
Ma'am...

24:09.297 --> 24:11.256
Governor Wallace did what
he promised to do.

24:11.341 --> 24:14.885
By being on the Tuscaloosa campus,
he kept the mob from gathering...

24:14.969 --> 24:17.095
Say, wasn't that Gump?

24:17.180 --> 24:21.266
- Nah, that couldn't be.
- It sure as hell was.

24:26.022 --> 24:27.856
A few years later,
that angry little man

24:27.940 --> 24:30.442
at the school house door
thought it would be a good idea

24:30.526 --> 24:32.694
and ran for president.

24:35.782 --> 24:38.450
But somebody thought that it wasn't.

24:40.161 --> 24:42.204
But he didn't die.

24:46.793 --> 24:48.460
My bus is here.

24:49.170 --> 24:52.297
- Is it the number nine?
- No, it's the number four.

24:53.299 --> 24:55.467
It was nice talking to you.

24:58.388 --> 25:02.474
I remember when that happened,
when Wallace got shot.

25:03.351 --> 25:04.810
I was in college.

25:04.894 --> 25:06.103
Did you go to a girls' college,

25:06.187 --> 25:08.021
or to a girls-and-boys-together college?

25:08.147 --> 25:09.147
It was co-ed.

25:09.232 --> 25:11.942
'Cause Jenny went to a college
I couldn't go to.

25:12.026 --> 25:14.361
It was a college just for girls.

25:14.487 --> 25:17.656
But I'd go and visit her
every chance I got.

25:48.396 --> 25:50.021
That hurts.

26:00.783 --> 26:02.951
Forrest! Forrest!

26:05.204 --> 26:08.123
- Forrest, stop it! Stop it!
Jesus!

26:08.207 --> 26:09.332
What are you doing?

26:09.417 --> 26:11.084
- He was hurting you.
- What the hell is going on here?

26:11.210 --> 26:14.880
- No, he's not! Get over there!
- Who is that? Who is that?

26:14.964 --> 26:16.047
- Billy, I'm sorry.
- What the hell?

26:16.132 --> 26:18.717
- Just get away from me!
- Don't...

26:18.801 --> 26:21.761
- Don't go! Billy, wait a second!
- Get away from me.

26:21.888 --> 26:24.055
He doesn't know any better!

26:25.807 --> 26:28.476
Forrest, why did you do that?

26:31.438 --> 26:34.398
I brought you some chocolate.

26:34.774 --> 26:36.484
I'm sorry.

26:38.653 --> 26:41.947
- I'll go back to my college now.
- Forrest...

26:45.660 --> 26:47.244
Look at you.

26:49.331 --> 26:51.415
Come on. Come on.

26:58.924 --> 27:00.799
- Is this your room?
- Shh!

27:05.263 --> 27:07.515
Do you ever dream, Forrest,

27:08.850 --> 27:11.685
about who you're gonna be?

27:11.770 --> 27:13.562
- Who I'm gonna be?
- Yeah.

27:13.647 --> 27:15.523
Aren't I going to be me?

27:15.607 --> 27:19.276
Well, you'll always be you,
just another kind of you.

27:20.195 --> 27:23.447
You know? I want to be famous.

27:25.158 --> 27:27.952
I want to be a singer like Joan Baez.

27:29.162 --> 27:32.289
I just want to be on an empty stage

27:32.374 --> 27:34.667
with my guitar, my voice.

27:36.503 --> 27:37.962
Just me.

27:39.464 --> 27:42.800
And I want to reach people
on the personal level.

27:45.470 --> 27:48.806
I want to be able to say things,
just one-to-one.

27:56.314 --> 27:59.191
Have you ever been with a girl, Forrest?

28:00.652 --> 28:04.488
I sit next to them in my Home
Economics class all the time.

28:33.435 --> 28:35.853
- I'm... Sorry.
- It's okay.

28:44.404 --> 28:46.113
It's all right.

28:48.950 --> 28:51.118
- It's okay.
- Oh, I'm dizzy.

28:59.793 --> 29:02.545
I bet that never happened in Home Ec.

29:07.384 --> 29:08.551
No.

29:14.767 --> 29:17.894
I think I ruined
your roommate's bathrobe.

29:17.978 --> 29:20.021
I don't care.
I don't like her, anyway.

29:20.105 --> 29:23.483
Run! Run! Run!

29:23.567 --> 29:28.071
- Run! Run! Run!
- Run! Run! Run!

29:35.996 --> 29:40.208
College ran by real fast,
'cause I played so much football.

29:40.292 --> 29:43.544
They even put me on a thing
called the All-America Team,

29:43.629 --> 29:47.423
where you get to meet
the President of the United States.

29:47.508 --> 29:49.092
President Kennedy met
with the Collegiate

29:49.176 --> 29:52.762
All-American Football Team
at the Oval Office today.

29:53.347 --> 29:55.348
Now, the really good thing
about meeting

29:55.432 --> 29:59.227
the President of the United States
is the food.

29:59.311 --> 30:02.021
They put you in this little room
with just about anything

30:02.106 --> 30:04.607
you'd want to eat or drink.

30:05.109 --> 30:08.569
And since, number one,
I wasn't hungry, but thirsty,

30:08.654 --> 30:11.322
and number two, they was free,

30:11.448 --> 30:14.492
I must have drank me about
15 Dr. Peppers.

30:17.454 --> 30:19.580
Congratulations.
How does it feel to be an All-American?

30:19.665 --> 30:21.416
It's an honor, sir.

30:21.500 --> 30:23.584
Congratulations.
How does it feel to be an All-American?

30:23.669 --> 30:25.294
Very good, sir.

30:26.130 --> 30:28.548
Congratulations.
How does it feel to be an All-American?

30:28.632 --> 30:30.383
Very good, sir.

30:30.467 --> 30:34.137
- Congratulations. How do you feel?
- I gotta pee.

30:34.805 --> 30:37.098
I believe he said
he had to "go pee. "

30:52.322 --> 30:55.199
Sometime later,
for no particular reason,

30:55.325 --> 30:57.702
somebody shot that
nice young President,

30:57.828 --> 31:00.204
when he was riding in his car.

31:00.831 --> 31:04.959
And a few years after that,
somebody shot his little brother, too,

31:05.043 --> 31:07.170
only he was in a hotel kitchen.

31:08.630 --> 31:11.048
It must be hard being brothers.

31:12.050 --> 31:13.259
I wouldn't know.

31:13.844 --> 31:15.219
Forrest Gump.

31:15.345 --> 31:16.596
Now can you believe it?

31:16.680 --> 31:20.600
After only five years of playing football,
I got a college degree.

31:20.684 --> 31:22.684
Congratulations, son.

31:23.478 --> 31:25.520
Mama was so proud.

31:26.856 --> 31:30.692
Forrest, I'm so proud of you.
Here, I'll hold this for you.

31:30.818 --> 31:32.903
Congratulations, son.

31:33.029 --> 31:36.031
Have you given any thought
to your future?

31:37.867 --> 31:39.201
Thought?

31:40.661 --> 31:42.496
Hello, I'm Forrest. Forrest Gump.

31:42.580 --> 31:45.582
Nobody gives a hunk of shit
who you are, fuzzball!

31:45.708 --> 31:48.335
You're not even a low-life,
scum-sucking maggot!

31:48.419 --> 31:52.380
Get your faggotty ass on the bus.
You're in the Army now!

31:52.715 --> 31:54.508
This seat's taken.

31:56.385 --> 31:57.761
Taken.

32:00.681 --> 32:03.475
At first, it seemed like
I made a mistake,

32:03.559 --> 32:05.602
seeing how it was only my induction day

32:05.728 --> 32:08.438
and I was already getting yelled at.

32:11.526 --> 32:13.777
You can sit down if you want to.

32:13.903 --> 32:17.739
I didn't know who I might meet,
or what they might ask.

32:17.865 --> 32:20.450
You ever been on a real shrimp boat?

32:20.952 --> 32:24.579
No, but I been on a real big boat.

32:25.373 --> 32:28.166
I'm talking about
a shrimp-catching boat.

32:28.251 --> 32:30.752
I've been working
on shrimp boats all my life.

32:30.878 --> 32:33.630
I started out on my uncle's boat,
that's my mama's brother,

32:33.756 --> 32:35.799
when I was about maybe nine.

32:35.925 --> 32:40.053
I was just looking into buying a boat
of my own and got drafted.

32:40.888 --> 32:45.767
My given name is Benjamin Buford Blue.
People call me Bubba.

32:46.435 --> 32:50.063
Just like one of them old redneck boys.
Can you believe that?

32:50.147 --> 32:53.817
My name's Forrest Gump.
People call me Forrest Gump.

32:54.777 --> 32:57.195
So, Bubba was from
Bayou La Batre, Alabama,

32:57.280 --> 32:59.197
and his mama cooked shrimp,

33:01.450 --> 33:04.327
and her mama before her
cooked shrimp,

33:04.453 --> 33:07.414
and her mama before her mama
cooked shrimp, too.

33:07.498 --> 33:08.707
Bubba's family knew everything

33:08.791 --> 33:11.418
there was to know
about the shrimping business.

33:11.502 --> 33:14.546
I know everything there is to know
about the shrimping business.

33:14.630 --> 33:17.632
Matter of fact, I'm going into
the shrimping business for myself

33:17.758 --> 33:20.093
after I get out the Army.

33:22.763 --> 33:23.805
Okay.

33:24.015 --> 33:28.101
Gump! What's your sole purpose
in this Army?

33:28.185 --> 33:30.729
To do whatever you tell me,
Drill Sergeant!

33:30.813 --> 33:34.190
God damn it, Gump!
You're a goddamn genius!

33:34.317 --> 33:36.651
That's the most outstanding answer
I've ever heard.

33:36.777 --> 33:39.529
You must have a goddamn IQ of 160!

33:39.655 --> 33:42.616
You are goddamn gifted, Private Gump!

33:43.618 --> 33:45.493
Listen up, people!

33:45.620 --> 33:49.788
Now, for some reason, I fit in
the Army like one of them round pegs.

33:49.873 --> 33:51.123
It's not really hard.

33:51.207 --> 33:54.835
You just make your bed real neat
and remember to stand up straight,

33:54.961 --> 33:58.923
and always answer every question
with, "Yes, Drill Sergeant!"

33:59.007 --> 34:00.466
Is that clear?

34:00.550 --> 34:02.676
- Yes, Drill Sergeant!
- Yes, Drill Sergeant!

34:03.178 --> 34:06.472
What you do is, you just drag
your nets along the bottom.

34:06.556 --> 34:10.309
On a good day, you can catch over
100 pounds of shrimp.

34:10.393 --> 34:13.812
If everything goes all right,
two men shrimping 10 hours,

34:13.897 --> 34:16.607
less what you spend on gas, you can...

34:16.690 --> 34:19.485
- Done, Drill Sergeant!
- Gump!

34:21.862 --> 34:24.614
Why did you put that weapon
together so quickly, Gump?

34:24.699 --> 34:26.367
You told me to, Drill Sergeant.

34:26.493 --> 34:29.911
Jesus H. Christ,
this is a new company record.

34:30.038 --> 34:32.498
If it wouldn't be a waste
of such a damn fine enlisted man,

34:32.581 --> 34:34.875
I'd recommend you for OCS,
Private Gump.

34:35.001 --> 34:36.835
You are gonna be
a general some day, Gump.

34:36.920 --> 34:40.005
Now, disassemble your weapon
and continue!

34:42.092 --> 34:45.886
Anyway, like I was saying,
shrimp is the fruit of the sea.

34:45.971 --> 34:50.724
You can barbecue it,
boil it, broil it, bake it, sautÃ© it.

34:50.809 --> 34:53.811
There's shrimp kebabs, shrimp Creole...

34:54.103 --> 34:58.941
...shrimp gumbo, pan fried,
deep fried, stir fried.

34:59.275 --> 35:02.820
There's pineapple shrimp,
lemon shrimp,

35:02.904 --> 35:05.239
coconut shrimp, pepper shrimp...

35:05.573 --> 35:11.537
...shrimp soup, shrimp stew,
shrimp salad, shrimp and potatoes,

35:11.621 --> 35:14.665
shrimp burger, shrimp sandwich...

35:17.252 --> 35:19.586
That's... That's about it.

35:23.299 --> 35:26.260
Night time in the Army
is a lonely time.

35:27.137 --> 35:30.764
We'd lay there in our bunks
and I'd miss my mama.

35:31.349 --> 35:33.851
And I'd miss Jenny.

35:37.772 --> 35:41.650
Hey, Gump, get a load of the tits on her!

35:55.123 --> 35:58.250
Turns out, Jenny had gotten into
some trouble over

35:58.334 --> 36:01.670
some photos of her
in her college sweater,

36:01.796 --> 36:04.339
and she was thrown out of school.

36:07.886 --> 36:10.095
But that wasn't a bad thing,

36:10.180 --> 36:13.766
because a man who owns
a theater in Memphis, Tennessee,

36:13.850 --> 36:18.895
saw those photos and offered Jenny
a job singing in a show.

36:19.688 --> 36:21.522
The first chance I got,

36:21.648 --> 36:25.318
I took the bus up to Memphis
to see her perform in that show.

36:25.402 --> 36:26.903
That was Amber, Amber Flame.

36:26.987 --> 36:29.447
Give her a big hand, guys.
Good job, Amber.

36:29.531 --> 36:32.283
And now, for your listening
and viewing pleasure,

36:32.367 --> 36:36.204
direct from Hollywood, California,
our very own beatnik beauty,

36:36.330 --> 36:39.999
let's give a big round of applause
to the luscious Bobbi Dylan.

36:42.169 --> 36:44.420
All right!
Bobbi!

37:07.361 --> 37:09.445
Her dream had come true.

37:10.697 --> 37:12.698
She was a folk singer.

37:21.959 --> 37:24.210
Come on, baby. Shake it up.
Shake it up, now.

37:24.294 --> 37:25.795
Hey, buddy, get her a harmonica.

37:29.550 --> 37:31.592
Hey, honey,
this ain't Captain Kangaroo.

37:31.718 --> 37:34.262
Hey, honey,
I got something here for you.

37:35.305 --> 37:39.058
- God damn it!
- Hey! Hey! Stupid jerk!

37:39.143 --> 37:41.602
I'm singing a song here.

37:43.939 --> 37:46.357
Polly, get out here!

37:46.441 --> 37:48.151
- Shut up, there!
Don't be so shy, honey.

37:48.235 --> 37:49.777
Oh, shut up!

37:52.447 --> 37:55.199
Forrest, what are you doing here?

37:55.284 --> 37:56.993
- What are you doing?
Hey!

37:57.077 --> 37:58.452
- Come on.
- What are you doing?

37:58.579 --> 38:00.580
Forrest, let me down!

38:06.420 --> 38:08.337
You can't keep doing this, Forrest.

38:08.422 --> 38:10.506
You can't keep trying
to rescue me all the time.

38:10.591 --> 38:14.677
- They was trying to grab you.
- A lot of people try to grab me.

38:15.596 --> 38:18.764
Just... You can't keep
doing this all the time.

38:19.266 --> 38:22.185
I can't help it. I love you.

38:23.145 --> 38:26.647
Forrest, you don't know what love is.

38:33.947 --> 38:36.949
You remember that time
we prayed, Forrest?

38:37.826 --> 38:42.330
We prayed for God to turn me
into a bird so I could fly far, far away?

38:44.291 --> 38:45.666
Yes, I do.

38:49.629 --> 38:52.464
You think I could fly off this bridge?

38:59.138 --> 39:01.306
What do you mean, Jenny?

39:05.186 --> 39:06.686
Nothing.

39:09.649 --> 39:11.691
I gotta get out of here.

39:13.986 --> 39:15.070
Wait, Jenny...

39:15.154 --> 39:19.616
Forrest, you stay away from me, okay?
You just stay away from me, please.

39:19.700 --> 39:20.992
Can I have a ride?

39:21.077 --> 39:22.619
Where you going?
- I don't care.

39:22.703 --> 39:24.079
Get in the truck.

39:24.163 --> 39:25.997
So, bye-bye, Jenny.

39:28.501 --> 39:30.835
They sending me to Vietnam.

39:33.589 --> 39:36.007
It's this whole other country.

39:38.511 --> 39:40.512
Just hang on a minute.

39:41.931 --> 39:44.975
Listen, you promise me
something, okay?

39:45.059 --> 39:48.395
Just, if you're ever in trouble,
don't try to be brave. You just run, okay?

39:48.521 --> 39:50.105
Just run away.

39:51.357 --> 39:52.691
Okay.

39:57.571 --> 39:58.905
Jenny.

40:00.783 --> 40:03.076
I'll write you all the time.

40:12.211 --> 40:15.213
And just like that,
she was gone.

40:31.314 --> 40:34.649
You come back safe to me,
do you hear?

41:17.942 --> 41:21.904
Now, they told us that Vietnam
was gonna be very different

41:21.988 --> 41:24.865
from the United States of America.

41:24.949 --> 41:29.995
And except for all the beer cans
and the barbecue, it was.

41:40.131 --> 41:43.217
Hey, I bet there's shrimp
all in these waters.

41:43.301 --> 41:46.470
They tell me these Vietnams
is good shrimpers.

41:46.554 --> 41:50.099
You know, after we win this war,
and we take over everything,

41:50.183 --> 41:51.392
we can get American shrimpers

41:51.476 --> 41:53.227
to come out here
and shrimp these waters.

41:53.311 --> 41:54.853
We'll just shrimp all the time, man.

41:54.979 --> 41:58.148
So much shrimp, why,
you wouldn't believe it.

41:58.817 --> 42:00.734
You must be my FNGs.

42:00.819 --> 42:02.069
- Morning, sir!
- Morning, sir!

42:02.153 --> 42:04.780
Get your hands down! Do not salute me.

42:04.864 --> 42:06.990
There's goddamn snipers
all around this area

42:07.075 --> 42:09.910
who would love to grease an officer.

42:09.994 --> 42:13.497
I'm Lieutenant Dan Taylor.
Welcome to Fourth Platoon.

42:14.374 --> 42:16.792
What's wrong with your lip?

42:16.876 --> 42:19.253
I was born with big gums, sir.

42:19.337 --> 42:24.049
Yeah, well, you better tuck that in.
Gonna get that caught on a trip wire.

42:25.218 --> 42:26.593
Where you boys from in the world?

42:26.678 --> 42:29.054
- Alabama, sir!
- Alabama, sir!

42:29.764 --> 42:31.265
You twins?

42:33.351 --> 42:35.769
No, we are not relations, sir.

42:38.022 --> 42:40.941
Look, it's pretty basic here.

42:41.734 --> 42:44.194
If you stick with me
and learn from the guys

42:44.279 --> 42:46.947
who've been in country a while,
you'll be all right.

42:47.031 --> 42:48.949
There is one item of GI gear

42:49.033 --> 42:53.203
that can be the difference between
a live grunt and a dead grunt.

42:53.538 --> 42:56.707
Socks. Cushion sole, OD green.

42:56.791 --> 42:58.083
Try and keep your feet dry.

42:58.209 --> 42:59.626
When we're out humping,
I want you boys to remember

42:59.711 --> 43:02.171
to change your socks whenever we stop.

43:02.255 --> 43:05.215
The Mekong will eat a grunt's feet
right off his legs.

43:05.300 --> 43:07.593
Sergeant Sims, God damn it,

43:07.719 --> 43:09.136
where is that sling rope
I told you to order?

43:09.220 --> 43:11.138
I put in the requisitions at Battalion.

43:11.222 --> 43:13.223
Yeah, yeah, yeah, well,
you call those sons of bitches again...

43:13.308 --> 43:15.851
Lieutenant Dan
sure knew his stuff.

43:15.935 --> 43:18.228
I felt real lucky he was my lieutenant.

43:18.980 --> 43:22.441
He was from a long,
great military tradition.

43:22.650 --> 43:25.736
Somebody in his family
had fought and died

43:26.738 --> 43:30.991
in every single American war.

43:31.910 --> 43:33.911
- God damn it, kick some ass!
- I'm on it, Lieutenant.

43:33.995 --> 43:35.120
Get on it!

43:35.246 --> 43:38.582
I guess you could say he had
a lot to live up to.

43:40.293 --> 43:45.129
So, you boys are from Arkansas, huh?
Well, I've been through there.

43:45.255 --> 43:47.423
Little Rock's a fine town.

43:48.091 --> 43:51.677
Now, go shake down your gear,
see the platoon sergeant,

43:51.762 --> 43:54.222
draw what you need for the field.

43:54.306 --> 43:58.267
If you boys are hungry,
we got steaks burning right over here.

43:58.352 --> 44:01.229
Two standing orders in this platoon:

44:01.313 --> 44:03.981
One, take good care of your feet,

44:04.107 --> 44:09.153
two, try not to do anything stupid,
like getting yourself killed.

44:15.619 --> 44:17.703
I sure hope I don't let him down.

44:29.299 --> 44:31.801
I got to see
a lot of the countryside.

44:31.885 --> 44:34.220
We would take these real long walks.

44:42.688 --> 44:46.816
And we were always looking
for this guy named Charlie.

44:54.658 --> 44:56.909
Hold it up!
Hold up, boys!

44:59.746 --> 45:02.081
It wasn't always fun.

45:02.165 --> 45:06.460
Lieutenant Dan was always getting
these funny feelings about a rock,

45:06.545 --> 45:11.632
or a trail, or the road,
so he'd tell us to get down, shut up...

45:11.717 --> 45:13.718
Get down! Shut up!

45:14.678 --> 45:16.137
...so we did.

45:33.697 --> 45:35.865
Now, I don't know much about anything,

45:35.949 --> 45:39.785
but I think some of America's
best young men served in this war.

45:39.870 --> 45:42.580
There was Dallas, from Phoenix,

45:44.291 --> 45:47.084
Cleveland, he was from Detroit.

45:47.210 --> 45:49.587
Hey, Tex. Hey, Tex.

45:49.713 --> 45:51.881
Man, what the hell's going on?

45:51.965 --> 45:56.302
And Tex was... Well, I don't remember
where Tex come from.

45:56.386 --> 45:57.928
Nothing.

46:02.059 --> 46:04.560
Fourth Platoon, on your feet.

46:04.645 --> 46:08.356
Still got 10 klicks to go to that river.
Move out.

46:08.440 --> 46:10.232
Come on, move out.

46:12.276 --> 46:14.694
Step it up. Look alive out there.

46:14.779 --> 46:19.115
The good thing about Vietnam
is there was always some place to go.

46:19.241 --> 46:20.617
Fire in the hole!

46:24.080 --> 46:26.414
Gump, check out that hole.

46:26.499 --> 46:29.501
And there was always something to do.

46:29.585 --> 46:32.754
- Mount them up.
Spread out! Cover his back.

46:37.802 --> 46:43.431
One day, it started raining,
and it didn't quit for four months.

46:44.433 --> 46:47.310
We'd been through
every kind of rain there is:

46:47.436 --> 46:49.979
Little bitty stinging rain,

46:50.690 --> 46:53.358
and big old fat rain,

46:53.818 --> 46:56.528
rain that flew in sideways.

46:56.612 --> 47:00.657
And sometimes, rain even seemed
to come straight up from underneath.

47:02.451 --> 47:04.828
Shoot, it even rained at night.

47:05.871 --> 47:08.331
- Hey, Forrest.
- Hey, Bubba.

47:08.457 --> 47:11.751
I'm gonna lean up against you.
You just lean right back against me.

47:11.836 --> 47:15.672
This way, we don't have to sleep
with our heads in the mud.

47:16.632 --> 47:20.093
You know why we a good partnership,
Forrest?

47:20.177 --> 47:22.679
'Cause we be watching out
for one another,

47:22.805 --> 47:24.681
like brothers and stuff.

47:26.642 --> 47:30.311
Hey, Forrest, there's something
I've been thinking about.

47:30.396 --> 47:33.398
I got a very important question
to ask you.

47:35.025 --> 47:38.987
How would you like to go
into the shrimping business with me?

47:40.156 --> 47:41.781
Okay.

47:41.866 --> 47:45.326
Man, I tell you what,
I got it all figured out, too.

47:45.411 --> 47:48.204
So many pounds of shrimp
to pay off the boat,

47:48.330 --> 47:51.624
so many pounds for gas,
we can just live right on the boat.

47:51.709 --> 47:54.002
We ain't got to pay no rent.

47:54.086 --> 47:56.171
I'll be the captain,
we can just work it together,

47:56.255 --> 48:00.508
split everything right down the middle.
Man, I'm telling you, 50-50.

48:00.593 --> 48:04.179
And, hey, Forrest,
all the shrimp you can eat.

48:05.723 --> 48:07.515
That's a fine idea.

48:08.601 --> 48:10.727
Bubba did have a fine idea.

48:14.523 --> 48:17.609
I even wrote Jenny
and told her all about it.

48:18.402 --> 48:21.613
I sent her letters,
not every day, but almost.

48:21.697 --> 48:26.701
I told her what I was doing
and asked her what she was doing,

48:26.786 --> 48:29.537
and told her
how I thought about her always,

48:30.873 --> 48:33.833
and how I was looking forward
to getting a letter from her

48:33.918 --> 48:36.419
just as soon as she had the time.

